00:29:19.189 --> 00:29:22.319
tried to look at, we've tried to put people

493
00:29:22.319 --> 00:29:26.540
in situations, not real life situations, but simulated situations

494
00:29:27.119 --> 00:29:30.180
where they have to think about their partner, um,

495
00:29:30.819 --> 00:29:36.000
engaging in behavior with another potentially attractive person. Um,

496
00:29:36.030 --> 00:29:38.680
AND to indicate how they would feel and think

497
00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:44.020
and what they might do as the apparent relationship,

498
00:29:44.040 --> 00:29:45.599
if you want to call it that, between their

499
00:29:45.599 --> 00:29:48.790
partner and this other attractive person as they're watching

500
00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:52.510
a situation unfolds. And what we've found is that

501
00:29:53.199 --> 00:29:55.369
Um, and this is consistent with other work in

502
00:29:55.369 --> 00:29:59.530
the field is that anxious people start out, even

503
00:29:59.530 --> 00:30:03.170
if there's minimal interaction between their partner and someone

504
00:30:03.170 --> 00:30:07.089
else who might be a viable rival, they start

505
00:30:07.089 --> 00:30:10.910
out being more jealous and avoidant more secure people.

506
00:30:11.410 --> 00:30:15.369
And as, as the partner and this other person

507
00:30:15.369 --> 00:30:18.849
kind of interact more and, and they, they get

508
00:30:18.849 --> 00:30:22.180
a little bit closer. They maintain that high level

509
00:30:22.180 --> 00:30:25.400
of distress and they're more likely to try to

510
00:30:25.400 --> 00:30:29.359
intervene and stop the situation even before a lot

511
00:30:29.359 --> 00:30:32.040
of people would say it's not really a problem

512
00:30:32.040 --> 00:30:36.459
yet, right? And so, and avoiding people basically, they,

513
00:30:36.520 --> 00:30:40.040
they suppress the jealousy. They say, oh, my partner

514
00:30:40.040 --> 00:30:43.119
is just being my partner. There's nothing going on

515
00:30:43.119 --> 00:30:46.300
here. I really don't care. So you've got the

516
00:30:46.439 --> 00:30:49.439
anxious people being hypervigilant, kind of being ready to

517
00:30:49.439 --> 00:30:52.670
see a problem before there really is a problem,

518
00:30:52.959 --> 00:30:54.890
and you've got the avoidant people down here saying,

519
00:30:55.439 --> 00:30:57.430
I'm going to dismiss it. I'm going to ignore

520
00:30:57.430 --> 00:30:59.640
it. I'm going to deny something is going on

521
00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:03.560
here until it's a real clear situation, and at

522
00:31:03.560 --> 00:31:06.239
that point then they intervene and they get upset.

523
00:31:07.020 --> 00:31:08.680
Secure people are kind of right in the middle.

524
00:31:09.140 --> 00:31:11.339
They're kind of like viewing it as the way

525
00:31:11.339 --> 00:31:14.130
most people would view it, you know. It starts

526
00:31:14.130 --> 00:31:17.420
out, uh, probably OK, then it gets a bit

527
00:31:17.420 --> 00:31:19.859
more intimate. Uh, I'm, I'm not going to pay

528
00:31:19.859 --> 00:31:21.579
attention to this. Then it gets more intimate and

529
00:31:21.579 --> 00:31:23.839
they think, oh, maybe I should do something, and

530
00:31:23.839 --> 00:31:26.459
then at some point they actually do something. Mhm

531
00:31:28.069 --> 00:31:33.510
How about personality traits? Does attachment relate to personality

532
00:31:33.510 --> 00:31:36.349
traits in any way? Uh, I mean, and when

533
00:31:36.349 --> 00:31:40.109
I say personality traits, it could be, I don't

534
00:31:40.109 --> 00:31:42.989
know, the big five, the exo, or some other

535
00:31:42.989 --> 00:31:44.810
inventory. So

536
00:31:45.430 --> 00:31:49.349
that's another really good question and um uh. Several

537
00:31:49.349 --> 00:31:51.280
people have done work on this. Chris Fraley at

538
00:31:51.280 --> 00:31:55.119
Illinois, for example, has, I believe, and there are

539
00:31:55.119 --> 00:31:56.880
others. We've done a little bit of work on

540
00:31:56.880 --> 00:31:59.959
this, um, and one of the things that we

541
00:31:59.959 --> 00:32:04.459
found is that there is a link actually between

542
00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:10.739
the degree of security, um, secure versus insecure, and

543
00:32:10.739 --> 00:32:13.859
three of the five big five traits. So, for

544
00:32:13.859 --> 00:32:17.239
example, people who have a history of being secure,

545
00:32:17.500 --> 00:32:22.069
starting early in life actually tend to become adults

546
00:32:22.319 --> 00:32:27.530
that are more agreeable, are more conscientious. And are

547
00:32:27.530 --> 00:32:30.829
less neurotic. Those three traits are the big five.

548
00:32:31.569 --> 00:32:33.890
AND that, those three traits form a higher level

549
00:32:33.890 --> 00:32:39.089
dimension that personality psychologists calls call stability. So, stability

550
00:32:39.089 --> 00:32:42.729
is you agree with people, you cooperate with them,

551
00:32:42.810 --> 00:32:46.569
you take their perspective, you are conscientious, you pay

552
00:32:46.569 --> 00:32:48.250
attention to what's going on, you try to do

553
00:32:48.250 --> 00:32:52.050
the right thing, and you're not neurotic. You're not

554
00:32:52.050 --> 00:32:56.410
focusing. AND ruminating on, on the negative things that

555
00:32:56.410 --> 00:32:59.410
are happening or could happen in the context of

556
00:32:59.410 --> 00:33:04.089
your relationships. And so, so security is or the

557
00:33:04.089 --> 00:33:08.099
degree of security. Going from secure to insecure is

558
00:33:08.099 --> 00:33:11.609
correlated with the stability dimension in the big five,

559
00:33:11.660 --> 00:33:14.819
and there's some other personality traits that are correlated

560
00:33:14.819 --> 00:33:17.300
with some of the big five measures that also

561
00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:21.180
correlate with attachment, but the important, an important point

562
00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:23.319
to make is that these correlations are not huge.

563
00:33:23.739 --> 00:33:25.880
So for example, in the study that we did,

564
00:33:25.979 --> 00:33:29.140
we're looking at a person's history of security measured

565
00:33:29.140 --> 00:33:32.239
in different ways. And they're standing on the big

566
00:33:32.239 --> 00:33:34.920
five traits of stability, the correlations were in the

567
00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:39.239
order of about 0.30, approximately. So you're accounting for

568
00:33:39.239 --> 00:33:43.920
about approximately about 10% of the variation that exists

569
00:33:43.920 --> 00:33:47.119
between attachment and these traits. So they're not the

570
00:33:47.119 --> 00:33:50.400
same thing, but they, they do, they do intersect.

571
00:33:51.390 --> 00:33:51.400
Mhm.

572
00:33:53.020 --> 00:33:57.180
So I have one last question then. Do the

573
00:33:57.180 --> 00:34:04.180
kinds of attachment people develop influence their parenting practices

574
00:34:04.180 --> 00:34:04.859
in any way?

575
00:34:05.890 --> 00:34:09.010
Yes, indeed. And in fact, the early, the early

576
00:34:09.010 --> 00:34:14.810
work in developmental psychology was focused on that directly.

577
00:34:14.929 --> 00:34:19.050
So the early work in developmental psychology in measuring

578
00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:21.330
attachment in adults was to use what's called the

579
00:34:21.330 --> 00:34:25.408
adult attachment interview. Um, AND the adult attachment interview

580
00:34:25.408 --> 00:34:28.447
is about a 45 minute interview that asks people

581
00:34:28.447 --> 00:34:32.638
questions about their, their memories of their parents, the

582
00:34:32.638 --> 00:34:34.967
people who took care of them, also their memories

583
00:34:34.967 --> 00:34:36.529
of others who took care of them as they

584
00:34:36.529 --> 00:34:39.208
were growing up. So, they would ask questions about,

585
00:34:39.289 --> 00:34:43.208
you know, what, what, what words describe your parents,

586
00:34:43.289 --> 00:34:45.678
and they would then they would give examples of,

587
00:34:45.728 --> 00:34:48.228
you know, my parents were loving. Here's an example

588
00:34:48.529 --> 00:34:51.090
from my memory. Uh, AND then they, uh, it

589
00:34:51.090 --> 00:34:53.199
also asked questions about what happened when you were

590
00:34:53.199 --> 00:34:56.860
upset, when you were hurt, etc. AND it's coded,

591
00:34:56.870 --> 00:34:59.169
um, and you can, you can, uh, place people

592
00:34:59.169 --> 00:35:02.810
into categories or put them on dimensions of security

593
00:35:02.810 --> 00:35:08.209
versus insecurity, um, and that, that, uh, the AI

594
00:35:08.209 --> 00:35:11.610
then was used to look at how those parents

595
00:35:11.610 --> 00:35:16.370
who were secure or insecure, uh, parented their own

596
00:35:16.370 --> 00:35:20.010
children in a strange situation. Uh, WHICH is a

597
00:35:20.010 --> 00:35:23.229
threatening situation that you put parents and kids in,

598
00:35:24.030 --> 00:35:28.090
um, at about 1.5 or 2 years of age.

599
00:35:28.750 --> 00:35:32.370
Um, AND what, so that work found that people

600
00:35:32.370 --> 00:35:35.090
who had a secure representation of how they were

601
00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:39.129
raised by their parents tended to have babies, children

602
00:35:39.129 --> 00:35:42.919
in this strange situation who, uh, when they were

603
00:35:42.919 --> 00:35:45.370
upset, would turn to them for comfort and would

604
00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:50.659
comfort quickly, whereas the insecure. People, people who had

605
00:35:50.659 --> 00:35:54.310
memories of their childhood that involved elements of either

606
00:35:54.310 --> 00:35:59.229
anxiety or avoidance. Um, WHEN they were videotaped in

607
00:35:59.229 --> 00:36:02.969
a strange situation with their children, their children either

608
00:36:03.800 --> 00:36:06.790
Did not come to them but remained distressed or

609
00:36:06.790 --> 00:36:09.510
came to them and never came calmed down. In

610
00:36:09.510 --> 00:36:12.669
other words, they couldn't comfort their children. And so

611
00:36:12.669 --> 00:36:15.350
there is a link there. There also is, there's

612
00:36:15.350 --> 00:36:17.510
been a little bit of work looking at the

613
00:36:17.510 --> 00:36:20.350
self-report adult attachment styles, which is a very different

614
00:36:20.350 --> 00:36:23.610
way of measuring things than the adult attachment interview,

615
00:36:23.989 --> 00:36:27.330
and that shows basically that you get somewhat similar

616
00:36:27.330 --> 00:36:28.989
results. In fact, we actually did some work on

617
00:36:28.989 --> 00:36:30.760
this about 30 years ago. It was the first

618
00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:35.449
work that was done. Looking at self-reported attachment to

619
00:36:35.449 --> 00:36:38.169
your romantic partner, predicting the way you parent your

620
00:36:38.169 --> 00:36:41.969
kid in a stressful situation. And what we found

621
00:36:41.969 --> 00:36:45.169
basically is results that kind of paralleled what was

622
00:36:45.169 --> 00:36:48.370
being found with the AAI. Now what's interesting about

623
00:36:48.370 --> 00:36:50.629
this is, at least in my opinion, is that

624
00:36:50.929 --> 00:36:55.199
the AAI does not correlate really highly. With the

625
00:36:55.209 --> 00:36:59.669
self-report romantic attachment measures that makes some sense because

626
00:36:59.689 --> 00:37:04.090
the AI measures your attachment based on memories when

627
00:37:04.090 --> 00:37:06.520
you were a child with your parents in one

628
00:37:06.520 --> 00:37:11.820
type of relationship. And the self-report romantic measures measure

629
00:37:12.080 --> 00:37:17.159
your more conscious representations of attachment in a different

630
00:37:17.159 --> 00:37:21.699
relationship, romantic, with a different person. Um, BUT when

631
00:37:21.699 --> 00:37:24.979
you look at the two together, they both kind

632
00:37:24.979 --> 00:37:29.250
of predict the same parenting styles. So secure parents,

633
00:37:29.840 --> 00:37:34.120
parents who are secure with their romantic partner, um,

634
00:37:34.379 --> 00:37:37.719
tend to be more sensitive, more caring, more empathic.

635
00:37:38.139 --> 00:37:42.780
Um, Parents who are insecure with their partner tend

636
00:37:42.780 --> 00:37:47.530
to either be hovering. Like anxious people kind of

637
00:37:47.530 --> 00:37:49.949
hovering over the kid, child and not letting them

638
00:37:49.949 --> 00:37:52.590
kind of do the task on their own, wanting

639
00:37:52.590 --> 00:37:54.590
to do it for them, or they tend to

640
00:37:54.590 --> 00:37:56.909
be more avoidant where they kind of like when

641
00:37:56.909 --> 00:37:59.510
the child fails at something, they kind of like

642
00:37:59.830 --> 00:38:02.750
rebuff them, dismiss them, you know, kind of view

643
00:38:02.750 --> 00:38:04.790
them as like, you know, come on, you could

644
00:38:04.790 --> 00:38:07.510
do better than that. And so it's interesting, we,

645
00:38:08.149 --> 00:38:09.179
this is one of the reasons why I think

646
00:38:09.179 --> 00:38:14.290
attachment theory is powerful because You can measure security

647
00:38:14.290 --> 00:38:17.129
with different people in different ways and you still

648
00:38:17.129 --> 00:38:20.290
see the same basic kinds of outcomes even though

649
00:38:20.290 --> 00:38:22.489
they're not necessarily always highly correlated.

650
00:38:23.719 --> 00:38:28.209
Yeah, no, that's really fascinating. So Dr. Simpson, just

651
00:38:28.209 --> 00:38:30.689
before we go, would you like to tell people

652
00:38:30.689 --> 00:38:33.530
where they can find your work on the internet?

653
00:38:34.979 --> 00:38:37.870
Uh, YEAH, if you go to the Department of

654
00:38:37.870 --> 00:38:41.870
Psychology at the University of Minnesota, um, there is

655
00:38:41.870 --> 00:38:45.479
a tab of faculty, and you can click on

656
00:38:45.699 --> 00:38:48.790
my link, and I've got a, uh, uh, a

657
00:38:48.790 --> 00:38:53.709
web page there that describes the most recent work

658
00:38:53.709 --> 00:38:57.250
that we've done. Um, I'm also on uh Orchid,

659
00:38:57.510 --> 00:38:59.139
uh, which lists all the things that I've done

660
00:38:59.139 --> 00:39:02.830
over the years, um, and, um, that probably is

661
00:39:02.830 --> 00:39:06.000
the best way to To, you know, find out

662
00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.199
what I'm doing, but there's a lot of good

663
00:39:08.199 --> 00:39:10.879
information out there on the internet on attachment. Attachment

664
00:39:10.879 --> 00:39:14.120
theory has become, and it's a grand theory basically

665
00:39:14.120 --> 00:39:16.280
of relationships. It's one of the 3 or 4

666
00:39:16.280 --> 00:39:19.439
biggest theories, and it's become, you know, one of

667
00:39:19.439 --> 00:39:24.020
the more popular, um, Popular theories, not only in

668
00:39:24.020 --> 00:39:27.419
academia, but also out there in the public. There's

669
00:39:27.419 --> 00:39:29.679
a lot of stuff on the, on the internet

670
00:39:29.679 --> 00:39:32.850
that allows you to kind of, uh, you know,

671
00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:36.129
take, take tests that measure your attachment, uh, your

672
00:39:36.129 --> 00:39:38.340
attachment styles and things like that. And I would

673
00:39:38.340 --> 00:39:41.139
also encourage, uh, folks to take a look at

674
00:39:41.139 --> 00:39:43.459
some of, of that information because there's a lot

675
00:39:43.459 --> 00:39:45.169
of it out there and a lot of it's

676
00:39:45.169 --> 00:39:46.810
actually pretty good. Mhm.

677
